    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A deposit of Ksh <m>100,000</m> is placed into a college fund at the beginning of every month for <m>10</m> years. The fund earns <m>9 \%</m> annual interest, compounded monthly, and paid at the end of the month. How much is in the account right after the last deposit?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The value of the initial deposit is Ksh <m>100,000</m>, so <m>a_{1}=100,000.</m> A total of <m>120</m> monthly deposits are made in the <m>10</m> years, so <m>n=120.</m> To find <m>r,</m> divide the annual interest rate by <m>12</m> to find the monthly interest rate and add <m>1</m> to represent the new monthly deposit.
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>r=1+\frac{0.09}{12}=1.0075</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute <m>a_{1}=100,000\text{ , }r=1.0075\text{ , }\text{ and }n=120</m> into the formula for the sum of the first <m>n</m> terms of a geometric series, and simplify to find the value of the annuity.</p>
            <p>
                <me>S_{120}=\frac{100,000(1-1.0075^{120})}{1-1.0075}≈19\text{ , }351,430</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                So the account has Ksh <m>19,351,430</m> after the last deposit is made.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A sofa set has a cash price of Ksh <m>50,000</m>. To buy it on hire purchase, a customer pays a deposit of Ksh <m>10,000</m> and <m>12</m> monthly installments of Ksh <m>4,000</m>. Calculate the annual flat rate of interest charged on the balance.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance} \amp = \;50,000 - 10,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 40,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total Paid in Installments} \amp = \; 12 \times 4,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 48,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Interest Paid} \amp = \; 48,000 - 40,000 = \text{Ksh}\; 8,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> I \amp = \; \frac{P \time R \times T}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> 8,000 \amp = \; \frac{40,000 \times R \times 1}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> 8,000 \amp = \; 400 R </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 20 \% \; \text{Per annum} </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A motorcycle costs Ksh <m>100,000</m> cash. A buyer pays a <m>20\%</m> deposit. The remaining balance is subject to compound interest at a rate of <m>15\%</m> p.a. for <m>2 </m> years. Calculate the total Hire Purchase Price.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Deposit:} \amp \; \frac{20}{100}\times 100,000 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 20,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance:} \amp \; 100,000 - 20,000 = \text{Ksh}\; 80,000</mrow>
                    <mrow> A \amp = \; P(1 + R)^T </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 80,000(1 + \frac{15}{100})^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 80,000 (1.15)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp \; 105,800 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\text{Total hire purchase} = 20,000 + 105,800 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 125,800 </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A laptop costs Ksh <m>40,000</m> cash. The hire purchase plan requires a Ksh <m>10,000</m> deposit and a flat interest rate of <m>10\%</m> p.a. If the monthly installment is Ksh <m>2,750</m>, how many months will it take to clear the debt?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance:} \amp \; 40,000 - 10,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 30,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Interest for 1 Year:} \; \amp \frac{10}{100} \times 30,000 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 3,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total instalments:} \amp \; 30,000 + 3,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 33,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Number of months:} \amp \; \frac{33,000}{2,750} = 12 \;\text{months} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

